{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637159","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637159"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:38:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17632"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17632","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17632"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.95,0.03,0.03,0,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10346"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71806"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10346","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10346"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17632"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57295"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10030"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24195"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24205"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24238"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71806","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71806"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe small intestine plays a crucial role in digestion and absorption of nutrients from ingested food.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes its primary function?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Absorption of nutrients across the epithelium","Absorption of water and electrolytes","Production of digestive enzymes","Secretion of hydrochloric acid","Storage of undigested food material"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of the small intestine is \u003Cstrong\u003Eabsorption of nutrients across the epithelium\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs mainly in the jejunum, which has extensive surface area due to circular folds, villi, and microvilli. Both active and passive transport mechanisms are involved in moving nutrients from the lumen into the bloodstream.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProduction of digestive enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E - While the small intestine produces some brush border enzymes, the majority of digestive enzymes come from the pancreas\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStorage of undigested food material\u003C/strong\u003E - This is a function of the large intestine, not the small intestine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESecretion of hydrochloric acid\u003C/strong\u003E - This occurs in the stomach, not the small intestine\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAbsorption of water and electrolytes\u003C/strong\u003E - While some water absorption occurs in the small intestine, this is primarily a function of the large intestine\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe small intestine\u0027s specialised structure, including its extensive surface area and rich blood supply, makes it uniquely suited for its primary role in nutrient absorption. Approximately 90% of nutrient absorption occurs in the small intestine.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The small intestine absorbs approximately 90% of ingested nutrients through its epithelial cells.","Most nutrient absorption occurs in the jejunum through both active and passive transport mechanisms.","The duodenum is primarily responsible for neutralising gastric acid and mixing chyme with pancreatic enzymes and bile."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57295"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17632"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"57295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/57295"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-20T16:03:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-20T16:03:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10346"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71806"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4928","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4928"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udca9","name":"Gastrointestinal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","